<h1>From George William Fairfax</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Dear Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Mount Vernon Septr 1st 1758</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>As soon as I despatched the People upon business, I thought it best to come over here<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0355-fn-0001" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0355-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> to see whether anything was necessary to have your further advice upon, for indeed the Oftener I come over the more I think it really necessary. For with regard to the Garrett Stairs I am at a loss unless I know whether you intend that for Lodging Appartments for Servts. If not the Stairs may be carried from the left hand room, which you design for Lumber, without making it publick. But if it is for Lodging 6 feet by 12 off from the old Store room will make a retired Stair, and leave a Closet with the Window of 8 by 12 which if not sufficient, you may make a good Room for the same uses above, and leave your Chambers intirely clear.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0355-fn-0002" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0355-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> If the Little Stairs (which will be directly opposite to you when you land from the other) will be an Eye-sore you may find a door which will make it uniform. The Landing you know is but narrow &amp; will be almost filled with Door, so that we shall be glad to know whether you intend only the small Vacancies between them to be Paperd, or the part, [(]supposing where ours is stocoed) to be also. I plainly see Mr Triplett cannot do your
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-05-02-pb-0439">[439]</span>
work, before the Frost, for what with Poseys and Major Wests work, He has not begun with the underpinning, but shall write to him immediately, and if he dont come shall employ any I can gett.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0355-fn-0003" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0355-fn-0003-ptr">3</a> He now and but lately said he coud not have time, and that your Carpenters must do the larthing Work Sir that you know ought to be done before the FrostsAnd I am sorry to say youl find it necessary to repair all your out HousesBut enough of this for fear you should be uneasy. And I will endeavour to direct for the best.</p>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0355-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter: a letter in the handwriting of the author ]">AL</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0355-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0355-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>See Fairfaxs letter written earlier in the day at Belvoir.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0355-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0355-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>GW chose this latter alternative.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0355-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0355-fn-0003">3</a>
   
   <p>For what William Triplett was expected to do at Mount Vernon, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0312" class="document">John Patterson to GW, 13 Aug.</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0312&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-05-02-0312-fn-0002#GEWN-02-05-02-0312-fn-0002" class="document">note 2 of that document</a>. John Posey, who at this time was captain of a company of artificers in the 2d Virginia Regiment, and John West<span class="choice deletion" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover_choice ] header=[]  body=[ Deleted: ', Sr.' &lt;span style='font-size: 90%'&gt;[[2008-09-28]]&lt;/span&gt; ]"><img alt="deletion" src="images/deletion_mark-trans.png" style="border:none;vertical-align: text-bottom; padding-right:2px"/></span> (d. 1777), were GWs neighbors at Mount Vernon. West lived on nearby Hunting Creek, and Poseys house was at Rovers Delight about a mile southwest of GWs house.</p>

</div>
